\section{Activist target selection} \label{sect:selection}
We examine the circumstances in which firms find themselves as the targets of activists. Table IA.1 reports the results of logistic regressions where the dependent variables are indicators for activism. The first column looks at the probability of being targeted for any kind of activism event, the second column examines the determinants of an activist making demands for board representation, and the third column examines the determinants of an activist getting representation on a firm’s board. Focusing on Column 1 of Table IA.1, we find that book-to-market is positively associated with activism, consistent with prior research (Brav et al. 2008) that found activists targeting undervalued firms. Also, we find that size-adjusted return is negatively associated with being targeted by activists, consistent with activists targeting poorly performing firms. In addition, consistent with prior research, we find that smaller companies are more likely to be targeted. However, the positive association between the proportion of independent directors (Outside percent) and activism is more challenging to explain in the same way, as some suggest this measure to be a proxy for good governance (Bhagat and Bolton 2008). One possible explanation is that a more independent board makes a firm more receptive to proposals from activists.

Turning to Column 2 of Table IA.1, we see evidence that activists are more likely to target a firm with demands for board representation when a greater portion of the firm’s shares are held by institutional investors, consistent with these investors being more open to supporting activists. Smaller firms are also more likely to be the target of board-related activism. In addition, we find that the board size is associated with the likelihood of being asked for board representation, consistent with the number of directors being a proxy for poor governance and activists targeting firms with worse governance (Yermack 1996).

In Column 3 of Table IA.1, we additionally find that activists are more likely to gain a board seat when the payout is lower, the institutional holding is higher, the return is lower, the firm is smaller, the book-to-market ratio is higher, and the board size is bigger with a higher number of outside directors. We examine whether these activist directors are more or less likely to be affiliated with activists in Table 8 of our main draft.

